      <script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ScholarlyArticle","author":[{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Person","name":"Jenny Bangham","url":"https://qmul.academia.edu/JennyBangham","image":"https://0.academia-photos.com/1952741/925401/36434336/s200_jenny.bangham.jpg","sameAs":[]}],"contributor":[],"dateCreated":"2016-10-25","datePublished":"2016-01-01","headline":"Invisibility and labour in the human sciences","image":"https://attachments.academia-assets.com/64504334/thumbnails/1.jpg","inLanguage":"en","keywords":[],"publication":"MPIWG Preprint [Max Planck Institute for the History of Science]","publisher":{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Organization","name":null},"sourceOrganization":[{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"EducationalOrganization","name":"qmul"}],"thumbnailUrl":"https://attachments.academia-assets.com/64504334/thumbnails/1.jpg","url":"https://www.academia.edu/29420773/Invisibility_and_labour_in_the_human_sciences"}</script><script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","about":{"@type":"ScholarlyArticle","name":"Invisibility and labour in the human sciences","url":"https://www.academia.edu/29420773/Invisibility_and_labour_in_the_human_sciences"},"mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What role does invisibility play in historical research practices?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The paper reveals that invisibility in research stems from multiple influences such as political context, archival practices, and the inherent dynamics of knowledge production. For instance, the work of translators often remains unrecognized despite their significant contributions to knowledge co-production."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do bureaucratic practices contribute to medical data collection invisibility?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The study finds that bureaucracies like the NIH facilitate systematic invisibility by erasing individual identities from clinical research narratives, as seen in the processes negotiated for the Normal Volunteer Patient Program initiated in 1953. This practice operates as a double-edged sword, enhancing medical knowledge while also concealing patient autonomy."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How did the Mass-Observation project redefine social and scientific inquiries?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Jardine's analysis demonstrates that the Mass-Observation project aimed to illuminate everyday life through participant-observer methodologies, which simultaneously produced statistical data while obscuring individual identities and nuances in behavior. The project exemplifies the tension between academic abstraction and the lived experiences of its participants."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the significance of citizen science dynamics in research visibility?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The workshop findings highlight that citizen science shifts the dynamics of visibility, as seen in the Xavante community’s active participation in scientific research while simultaneously seeking land rights and healthcare. This illustrates how marginalized groups leverage their roles to assert political visibility in scientific discourses."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How did perspectives on translators alter historical research outcomes?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Vongsathorn's work notes that perceptions of translators as mere facilitators limit recognition of their influence in shaping narrative content and access to knowledge. This reflects larger academic notions of authenticity, often sidelining the translators' contributions to the co-construction of knowledge through mediating language and culture."}}]}</script><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/design_system/default_tokens/rebrand-89afffb91e093c5385bc943212566acb82d8da08820977c439fbb6656b3d411c.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/single_work_page/loswp_redesigns/ungated_variant-396bbd21fb1213413912bc4f8905c077ab09f4e6f899c0094ab7368fc7fa8fa0.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/design_system/heading-95367dc03b794f6737f30123738a886cf53b7a65cdef98a922a98591d60063e3.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/design_system/body-c50f5ab98832f511df8842993148351135752147645352dc0b07c369bcb29ab7.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/design_system/button-4d6745f84a0a0d8316c46d93a0bc87b9c96d3bce729ca2b864b618764cddd832.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/design_system/text_button-d1941ab08e91e29ee143084c4749da4aaffa350a2ac6eec2306b1d7a352d911a.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/single_work_page/accordion-db99f5a0fda3c12c056b88b46879e95c504112cd02807f4c526634dfb6529288.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/single_work_page/ai_label-ce27a6e5844b0ce31dcb42cc62f5f415c06ca204b3d13705c41e2471d0fb65fd.css" media="all" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/single_work_page/ordered_list-9123030494f589694fc98dd7b689a70398eb527516b541b1c648dce5ab690c12.css" media="all" /><link as="fetch" crossorigin="anonymous" href="https://attachments.academia-assets.com/64504334/1.html" rel="preload" /><link rel="stylesheet" href="//a.academia-assets.com/assets/about_hiring/footer-4b1d1471325a90ac5ba51422db929bc292e3d4469d0fabb80d93ab2310ff2719.css" media="all" /><link rel="preload" href="//a.academia-assets.com/fonts/design_system/DM-Sans_100-1000_normal_latin.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin="anonymous"><link rel="preload" href="//a.academia-assets.com/fonts/design_system/Gupter_400_normal_latin.woff2" as="font" type="font/woff2" crossorigin="anonymous"><link rel="preload" href="//a.academia-assets.com/fonts/desi