itle">Abstract</h2><div class="ai-label ai-label--ungated"><img alt="sparkles" src="//a.academia-assets.com/images/icons/sparkle.svg" width="16" height="16" /><p class="ds2-5-body-xs">AI generated</p></div></summary><div class="safe-abstract--container"><div class="safe-abstract--body"><style>.truncate-component {
  position: relative;

  overflow: hidden;
  display: -webkit-box;
  line-clamp: 16;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 16;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
}

.toggle-truncation-button {
  display: none;
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 0;
  right: 0;
}</style><div class="truncate-component js-truncate-component--abstract"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">This paper explores the interplay between invisibility and labour within the human sciences, specifically through the lens of historical research. Organized as a result of a workshop, the discussion underscores the politics of representation and challenges conventional narratives about citizen participation in scientific research. It highlights how the dynamics of visibility and invisibility manifest across three domains: people, power, and process, prompting a reevaluation of who is seen and how societal roles shape scientific knowledge production.</p><div class="toggle-truncation-button js-toggle-truncation-button--abstract"><button class="safe-abstract--toggle-truncation-button"><span>... </span><span class="safe-abstract--toggle-truncation-button-text">Read more</span></button></div></div></div></div></details><details class="accordion js-loswp-accordion" data-section-name="Key takeaways" id="key-takeaways"><summary><h2 class="ds2-5-heading-sans-serif-md accordion-section__title">Key takeaways</h2><div class="ai-label ai-label--ungated"><img alt="sparkles" src="//a.academia-assets.com/images/icons/sparkle.svg" width="16" height="16" /><p class="ds2-5-body-xs">AI generated</p></div></summary><div class="ds-key-takeaways--container"><div class="key-takeaways--content"><ol class="ordered-list key-takeaways--list"><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">The workshop explores themes of visibility and invisibility in the human sciences, particularly regarding labor and representation.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Invisibility is dynamic, influenced by political and social contexts, affecting knowledge production and historical narratives.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Translators and research assistants significantly shape knowledge production yet often remain unacknowledged in scholarly outputs.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">The gender dynamics in historical research reveal how women&#39;s contributions can become invisible or underappreciated.</li><li class="ordered-list--item ds2-5-body-md">Historical practices of data collection, like those used for Roma populations, demonstrate how expertise can reinforce marginalization.</li></ol><script type="application/json" id="js-react-on-rails-context">{"componentRegistryTimeout":5000,"railsEnv":"production","inMailer":false,"i18nLocale":"en","i18nDefaultLocale":"en","rorVersion":"16.1.2","rorPro":true,"rorProVersion":"3.3.1","href":"https://www.academia.edu/29420773/Invisibility_and_labour_in_the_human_sciences","location":"/29420773/Invisibility_and_labour_in_the_human_sciences","scheme":"https","host":"www.academia.edu","port":null,"pathname":"/29420773/Invisibility_and_labour_in_the_human_sciences","search":null,"httpAcceptLanguage":null,"autoProps":{},"serverSide":false}</script>
<div id="FeatureFeedback-react-component-c1170fd0-60ac-4c52-b73e-c5172cf21c19"></div>
<script type="application/json" class="js-react-on-rails-component" id="js-react-on-rails-component-FeatureFeedback-react-component-c1170fd0-60ac-4c52-b73e-c5172cf21c19" data-component-name="FeatureFeedback" data-dom-id="FeatureFeedback-react-component-c1170fd0-60ac-4c52-b73e-c5172cf21c19">{"featureName":"key_takeaways"}</script></div></div></details><details class="accordion js-loswp-accordion" data-section-name="FAQ&#39;s" id="faq"><summary><h2 class="ds2-5-heading-sans-serif-md accordion-section__title">FAQ&#39;s</h2><div class="ai-label ai-label--ungated"><img alt="sparkles" src="//a.academia-assets.com/images/icons/sparkle.svg" width="16" height="16" /><p class="ds2-5-body-xs">AI generated</p></div></summary><div class="work-faq--container"><div class="work-faq--list"><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="1"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="What role does invisibility play in historical research practices?">What role does invisibility play in historical research practices?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">The paper reveals that invisibility in research stems from multiple influences such as political context, archival practices, and the inherent dynamics of knowledge production. For instance, the work of translators often remains unrecognized despite their significant contributions to knowledge co-production.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="2"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="How do bureaucratic practices contribute to medical data collection invisibility?">How do bureaucratic practices contribute to medical data collection invisibility?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">The study finds that bureaucracies like the NIH facilitate systematic invisibility by erasing individual identities from clinical research narratives, as seen in the processes negotiated for the Normal Volunteer Patient Program initiated in 1953. This practice operates as a double-edged sword, enhancing medical knowledge while also concealing patient autonomy.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="3"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="How did the Mass-Observation project redefine social and scientific inquiries?">How did the Mass-Observation project redefine social and scientific inquiries?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">Jardine&#39;s analysis demonstrates that the Mass-Observation project aimed to illuminate everyday life through participant-observer methodologies, which simultaneously produced statistical data while obscuring individual identities and nuances in behavior. The project exemplifies the tension between academic abstraction and the lived experiences of its participants.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="4"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="What is the significance of citizen science dynamics in research visibility?">What is the significance of citizen science dynamics in research visibility?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">The workshop findings highlight that citizen science shifts the dynamics of visibility, as seen in the Xavante community’s active participation in scientific research while simultaneously seeking land rights and healthcare. This illustrates how marginalized groups leverage their roles to assert political visibility in scientific discourses.</p></div></details><details class="work-faq--item" data-faq-number="5"><summary class="work-faq--question js-faq-question"><span class="work-faq--question-text" data-question="How did perspectives on translators alter historical research outcomes?">How did perspectives on translators alter historical research outcomes?</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined work-faq--icon" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">add</span></summary><div class="work-faq--answer"><p class="ds2-5-body-md">Vongsathorn&#39;s work notes that perceptions of translators as mere facilitators limit recognition of their influence in shaping narrative content and access to knowledge. This reflects larger academic notions of authenticity, often sidelining the translators&#39; contributions to the co-construction of knowledge through mediating language and culture.</p></div></details></div></div><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  function getCookie(name) {
    const value = `; ${document.cookie}`;
    const parts = value.split(`; ${name}=`);
    if (parts.length === 2) return parts.pop().split(';').shift();
  }

  const csrfToken = document.querySelector("[name='csrf-token']")?.content ??
    getCookie('masked_csrf_token');
  if (!csrfToken) {
